topics.description: The web's original architecture is decentralised, and for good reasons. Somehow, though, we managed to forget that throughout the last years. We use centralised services like twitter, facebook and gmail without thinking (or even blinking). I'm going to argue in this talk that decentralisation matters a lot because it makes the web resilient against technical and non technical threats which are, as we now know, thanks to Snowden, real and not only theoretical. What can we do about it? We need new technologies, but we also need to think about how to find forms of organisations and ways of doing business to accommodate decentralised structures. The future is, indeed, not equally distributed, and it is upon us to fix that.

topics.description:
Container based virtualization can revolutionize the way we deliver software. They simplify

  * running the exact same software stack in all environments
  * running the exact same software stack on all servers (even on our development machines)
  * do rapid deployments and rollbacks, as often as we want
  * do canary or red/green deployments
  * better utilize available resources

Docker (www.docker.io) makes it easy to manage LXC containers (the same technology Heroku is using behind the scenes) and enables us to build our own "private Heroku" to test and deliver our software. And the best thing: you can decide yourself if you want to run them on bare metal servers, the cloud or any cheap VPS. You can even use those advanced deployment techniques when your site still fits on one physical server.
topics.name: Docker

topics.description:
I gave this talk at RubyConf AU last week. I also gave this same talk at wroc_love.rb I'd like to share with my german friends as well!

Here's a situation we've all be in at one point. We have a program. We
want to make that program faster. We know about threads, processes,
fibers. Then you start programming and you have no clue what to do. I
was there. It sucks. This talk guides you down the rabbit hole and
brings out the other side.

Points covered:

* Threads, Fibers
* Processes, Forking, Detaching
* Parellelism vs Concurrency
* The many many different ways I crashed my computer learning these
  things
* Gotchas of each
* Common ways you shoot yourself in the foot
* Celluoid

This is a learning and informative talk. It's target at intermediate
developers who have ruby experience but never written any multi threaded
code.
topics.name: Dear God What Am I Doing? Concurrency and Parallel Processing

topics.description:
Die reibungslose Kommunikation zwischen den vielen einzelnen Teilen die heute eine große Anwendung ausmachen ist eine der wichtigsten Herausforderungen die wir als Entwickler zu lösen haben. Spätestens seit Anwendungen nicht mehr aus einem großen Stück Software sondern statdessen aus einem Haufen kleiner Services bestehen müssen wir uns etwas einfallen lassen, damit diese sich auch ohne großes Drama miteinander austauschen können.

Mein Vortrag gibt einen Überblick darüber wie wir dieses Problem bei Engine Yard mit der Einführung einer unternen PUBSUB Infrastruktur angegangen haben, über die Werkzeuge die wir dafür benutzt haben und die fatalen Fehler die wir dabei gemacht haben. Darüber hinaus zeige ich Potentiale auf die über die rein technischen Vorteile hinaus durch ein offenen Systems zur Kommunikation zwischen Services entstehen können und helfen eine produktivere Kultur in eurem Unternehmen zu schaffen.

* Wie nutzt man die Asset-Pipeline, was sind sinnvolle Erweiterungen (Compass etc.)
* Was macht bei der Asset-Pipeline ärger, warum will man das eventuell nicht
* Was sind die Alternativen (Rake-Pipeline etc.)

Ich bereite ein bisschen Material zur Einleitung vor, will aber ansonsten mit Euch (und vor allem Lennart) diskutieren.
topics.name: Assets, assets, assets (my ass)

topics.description: [oEmbed](http://oembed.com/) is an open format for embedding media from third-party providers, e.g. videos, pictures or tweets. It turns a URL into an embeddable representation of the media content. If, for example, a link to a video is shared on a blog or social network, it can automagically be turned into an embedded video. The talk starts with a summary of oembed considering both API provider and consumer. The second part focuses on how to turn a rails app into an oembed provider.

topics.description:
Ich möchte ein bisschen von meinen Erfahrungen in Neuseeland erzählen, von den guten **und** den schlechten. Ich
werde dabei Punkte wie *Visum, Jobsuche, Arbeitskultur, die allgemeine Kiwi-Mentalität, Natur, Lebenshaltung,
Kosten, Unterkunft, Wetter/Klima/Winter, Aktivitäten neben dem Job, Alltag und Kaffee* ansprechen.

Dies ist natürlich und mit Absicht kein technischer Vortrag. Ich möchte erzählen, wie es war, ohne zu beschönigen
oder schlecht zu machen, damit ihr euch ein Bild machen könnt. Und vielleicht auch, um euch dafür zu begeistern,

topics.description:
Die reibungslose Kommunikation zwischen den vielen einzelnen Teilen die heute eine große Anwendung ausmachen ist eine der wichtigsten Herausforderungen die wir als Entwickler zu lösen haben. Spätestens seit Anwendungen nicht mehr aus einem großen Stück Software sondern statdessen aus einem Haufen kleiner Services bestehen müssen wir uns etwas einfallen lassen, damit diese sich auch ohne großes Drama miteinander austauschen können.

Mein Vortrag gibt einen Überblick darüber wie wir dieses Problem bei Engine Yard mit der Einführung einer unternen PUBSUB Infrastruktur angegangen haben, über die Werkzeuge die wir dafür benutzt haben und die fatalen Fehler die wir dabei gemacht haben. Darüber hinaus zeige ich Potentiale auf die über die rein technischen Vorteile hinaus durch ein offenen Systems zur Kommunikation zwischen Services entstehen können und helfen eine produktivere Kultur in eurem Unternehmen zu schaffen.
topics.name: Improving Inter Service Communication

topics.description: Single page apps are all the rage - apps that use MVC JavaScript frameworks and a simple REST based API on the server side (if at all) to persists data are popping up all over the place and are especially popular as a relatively simple way of developing responsive and highly interactive mobile web applications. Enough of the buzzword bingo. Building single page apps comes with a whole new set of problems that are to solve: JS side templating and where to store the templates, how to create apps that are both working as single page apps and are indexable by the mighty google bot. Also: Testing, security, etc. This talk summarizes reasons for and agains building a single page app and tops it off with deeper looks into technical aspects of building a rich client app for the browser.

topics.description:

Die Beschreibung hier ist in Englisch formuliert, ich kann den Vortrag aber auch auf Deutsch halten.

> Distributed programming is hard. CouchDB aims to address multi-master data synchronisation and make it accessible to a wider audience of programmers.
> This talk explains the principles behind CouchDB’s powerful data synchronisation engine and follows up with a look at a number of different use-cases where it solves real world problems.
> Where applicable, we look at satellite projects PouchDB, TouchDB and BigCouch, the in-browser, mobile-OS, and BigData implementations of CouchDB replication.
 

Viele Grüße
Jan

topics.description:
I gave this talk at RubyConf AU last week. I also gave this same talk at wroc_love.rb I'd like to share with my german friends as well!

Here's a situation we've all be in at one point. We have a program. We
want to make that program faster. We know about threads, processes,
fibers. Then you start programming and you have no clue what to do. I
was there. It sucks. This talk guides you down the rabbit hole and
brings out the other side.

Points covered:

* Threads, Fibers
* Processes, Forking, Detaching
* Parellelism vs Concurrency
* The many many different ways I crashed my computer learning these
  things
* Gotchas of each
* Common ways you shoot yourself in the foot
* Celluoid

This is a learning and informative talk. It's target at intermediate
developers who have ruby experience but never written any multi threaded
code.
topics.name: Dear God What Am I Doing? Concurrency and Parallel Processing

topics.description:
Container based virtualization can revolutionize the way we deliver software. They simplify

  * running the exact same software stack in all environments
  * running the exact same software stack on all servers (even on our development machines)
  * do rapid deployments and rollbacks, as often as we want
  * do canary or red/green deployments
  * better utilize available resources

Docker (www.docker.io) makes it easy to manage LXC containers (the same technology Heroku is using behind the scenes) and enables us to build our own "private Heroku" to test and deliver our software. And the best thing: you can decide yourself if you want to run them on bare metal servers, the cloud or any cheap VPS. You can even use those advanced deployment techniques when your site still fits on one physical server.
topics.name: Docker

topics.description: The web's original architecture is decentralised, and for good reasons. Somehow, though, we managed to forget that throughout the last years. We use centralised services like twitter, facebook and gmail without thinking (or even blinking). I'm going to argue in this talk that decentralisation matters a lot because it makes the web resilient against technical and non technical threats which are, as we now know, thanks to Snowden, real and not only theoretical. What can we do about it? We need new technologies, but we also need to think about how to find forms of organisations and ways of doing business to accommodate decentralised structures. The future is, indeed, not equally distributed, and it is upon us to fix that.
topics.name: Decentralise ALL THE THINGS!
